Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment:
I loved this movie. I'm glad I gave it a chance. At first glance when I saw trailers for it on tv, the conflicting art styles turned me off. But upon finally viewing the movie a number of times, I've come to love the art choice and the movie itself even more. Because it fits the story. Arlo doesn't belong in the wild, he's meant to stand out. Whilst others find it too cartoony I find it brilliant. 

The story I felt was simplistic, perhaps derivative and borrowed many elements from other films, but that is sometime I learned to look past, but all films do in some ways, but it worked. It didn't need to be complex. it didn't need to be original. cliche isn't a bad thing. the Story of Arlo overcoming his fears and surviving in the wild, and watching his growth right from the start and righ to the very end, and his bond with spot which was heartwarming and felt organic, and the way it's told visually more than verbally is great. 

Also the subtle progression of Spots character from wild lonely "animal", back to a human boy, which starts when Arlo and Spot first make that connection due to a common loss and find comfort in each other because they are both alone in the wild, and just watching Spot slowly uncover his humanity and evolving at the end, by finally walking on two feet when he goes off with his new family was fantastic. 

I know this movie isn't a masterpiece, but I think the hate it gets is ridiculously unwarranted. Considering the production problems, the movie still turned out to be good, and still had that pixar magic. Could it have been better? yes it could have. But I appreciate it for how it turned out.

And you can't convince me that the movie doesn't feel like pixar or doesn't have that pixar magic, because those moments with arlo and spot are, charming, heartwarming, bittersweet, joyful, heart wrenching, pure pixar magic. That river scene with the sticks was truly powerful, and it was done with almost no dialogue all visually. I get it, if you didn't like the movie, more power to you. But it is FAR from bad which is what some people say and I just can't agree with that.

Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment: This movie was soo bad. First of all, the dinosaurs doesn't fit in with the realistic environment and also, the plot was a knock-off of both The Land Before Time and Yoshi's Island. In this movie Arlo is out on a journey to send Spot back to his family, and that's the same Yoshi does trying the get baby Mario and Luigi back home to their parents. And it rips off The Land Before Time explaining how things were when Dinosaurs ruled over and going on adventures, getting into many circumstances and fighting against it, finding your true potential, it's all the same as like what LittleFoot and his friends go through the same thing. Also, LittleFoot is much more braver than Arlo is. I'm not going on a full tirade but it's obviously The Land Before Time and Yoshi's Island mixed together and the animation isn't the best either. Movies like Zootopia and Big Hero 6, however, those were amazing.

Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment:
I love Disney and Pixar, but I must be honest:

I didn't care much for this movie, frankly. I found it almost boring. There were a few funny moments and some heartbreaking ones, sure, but other than that it didn't catch my interest - which was disappointing, because this trailer peaked my interest. And I didn't even mind the plenty scientific inaccuracies, because I know it's supposed to be a fantasy and it's clearly directed towards a younger audience. 

But, as stated, I was very disappointed. It didn't feel like Disney and Pixar tried their best. And yes, this subject is a challenge to make into a movie, but still.

Comment: I have to say, Disney/Pixar took a really heavy turn for this movie's trailer. Normally there would be a small introduction to the plot and give names of characters. But instead it showed a bunch of cool-looking dinosaurs and a feral kid. But nonetheless if the trailer took a turn, it took a turn for the better, because now I'm interested to see what the movie will bring up. Probably the same way inside out interested me to see it. Hope it will leave the same impression like the Croods did. Also a pet-peeve of mine with this movie. Cave-men and dinosaurs didn't live in the same era. But if we did, there wouldn't as much of the same animals today and we would've evolved differently than the way we are today.

Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment: People are taking movies way too seriously now. "This movie is so inaccurate!" You know what else is inaccurate? Toys come to life when nobody's looking, fish can speak and understand English, an old man can manage to gather enough balloons to fly his entire house all the way to South America,  a rat can befriend a human and learn how to cook, our closets are portals that lead to the monster world, and our emotions are tiny people in our brain that control everything we do! You'll enjoy the movie a lot more if you learn not to nitpick every little thing. In fact, instead of wasting my time arguing over a children's movie, I will eagerly wait for the movie and hopefully enjoy it.

Comment:
What if this wasn't in the past?

I think this will fit into the Pixar Theory as so;

It'll be placed between Bug's Life and Monster's University. After humans and animals start to return to Earth, Animals start to be the first to evolve from BnL's radiation, into dinosaur-type creatures(hence their cartoony look). The meteor is a second meteor that just so happened to miss Earth, letting the new dinosaur-like creatures and humans live together. However, after the animals evolved too much, and humans begin to become wiped out once more from the dinosaurs, they split off into primitive 'factions' or 'tribes', thus the caveman-ey look. After more time, the humans AND the dinosaurs will evolve from the BnL radiation, into monsters. That is why there are both Hairy and Lizard-like monsters, because of the Humans and Dinosaurs.

That's my theory, at least.

Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment: I'm sorry to say that I'm not all that impressed by what I've seen so far of this. As far as I can tell, storywise it looks like a rehash of the first Ice Age movie, only with dinosaurs replacing the mammoths and other mammals. The subarctic backdrop even looks almost the same! And even though these dinosaurs are supposed to be 65 million years removed from the Mesozoic ones we all know and love, they really don't look the part. They look like the old stock Mesozoic dinosaurs modeled in this ridiculously cartoonish style, which jars with their photo-realistic environment. I'll probably see it anyway when it comes out, but I don't expect much right now.

But has anyone thought why they had to design the characters that way? There are many reasons to come up with that solution and I thought deep into it. For me personally and its not the legitimate answer but, I believe its because Pixar's rendering for this animation has become so great....*it looks like live-action*. I mean seriously,  take out the dinosaurs and you got a movie on a live-action documentary on nature. Like they just went out with their cameras, and started filming landscapes and added CG dinosaurs into them. Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment: While I did mention this on a different video about this trailer, it bears repeating here as well. And before I say my main point, the film does look gorgeous. The details on each of the dinosaurs, to the water effects, to the rock texture, it's technically beautiful. With that said, it looks like the biggest problem with this movie, is the main Dino itself. I myself am not against the idea of having a kid-like Dinosaur as the protagonist, but there needs to be some form of consistency. It just doesn't feel right having lush, detailed, realistic environments being inhabited by a googly-eyed squash and stretch machine like the main Dino. That's not to say that squash and stretch effects are bad, but it needs to fit in with the rest of the movie. Maybe I could look past it if it was just like a side character that comes in for about 2 scenes, but this is the main character! Not to mention the clashing styles of having realistic skin on this goofy character is very distracting. I'm not saying the film won't be good, because knowing Pixar, it'll have a polished script, excellent visuals, and a lasting effect on kids, but I can't help but point out something so distracting.

Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment: While I did mention this on a different video about this trailer, it bears repeating here as well. And before I say my main point, the film does look gorgeous. The details on each of the dinosaurs, to the water effects, to the rock texture, it's technically beautiful. With that said, it looks like the biggest problem with this movie, is the main Dino itself. I myself am not against the idea of having a kid-like Dinosaur as the protagonist, but there needs to be some form of consistency. It just doesn't feel right having lush, detailed, realistic environments being inhabited by a googly-eyed squash and stretch machine like the main Dino. That's not to say that squash and stretch effects are bad, but it needs to fit in with the rest of the movie. Maybe I could look past it if it was just like a side character that comes in for about 2 scenes, but this is the main character! Not to mention the clashing styles of having realistic skin on this goofy character is very distracting. I'm not saying the film won't be good, because knowing Pixar, it'll have a polished script, excellent visuals, and a lasting effect on kids, but I can't help but point out something so distracting.

Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment: In an alternate timeline where Earth was never hit by an asteroid and dinosaurs never became extinct, a young Apatosaurus named Arlo loses his father in a tragic accident. One day, Arlo falls into a river and gets knocked out by a rock, finding himself far away from his home. While trying to find a way back to the Clawed-Tooth Mountains, he befriends a human cave-boy that he names Spot.

Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment: I guess I'll just be the odd one out here and say that I love the art direction for this film. The photo-realistic environments are simply breath-taking and I rather enjoy the cartoony look of the dinosaurs. It's an animated movie, it's Pixar, we all know the animation will end up being fantastic in the end. And this is sure looking like a movie that will be similar to WALL-E, where the whole story is told through music and visuals. I'm looking forward to it.

Comment:
I like how many folks are getting uptight about "Hey, dinos and humans didn't co-exist, and it could never happen!"
What if the mass-extinction event didn't occur?¬† Is it so impossible that mammals could have co-evolved along giant reptiles?¬† Maybe at a slower pace?¬† If the dinos are living in today's age, then human evolution WITH competition from them would be set back.. hence why they are only primitives "today" according to this alternative time-line.¬† Sure, it's highly improbable, but not impossible.¬† Especially for a kids' cartoon.
I'm more bothered by Arlo looking like an inflatable pool-toy against the environment.¬† Honestly would have preferred the backgrounds to have been equally cartoony.¬† But, *art!*, and all that that implies...

Comment:
I do not like the aesthetics of this movie. At all. End of story. Realistic environment with a jellow-plastic dinosaur does not fit. I was reading some of the comments, saying that its to make nature the antagonist, WHY ARE WE ANTAGONIZING NATURE IN THE FIRST PLACE?????????? Hate it when people do that. Also, MAKING SOMETHING REALISTIC SHOULD NOT MAKE IT AN ANTAGONIST.



And so, at the end of the day, this movie will suck visually. Maybe if they use dialogue and the viewers bonding to the characters correctly, they can bring an F to a D, possibly. Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment:
I'm still kinda irked with this cartoony character design contrasting the gorgeous realistic landscapes. I felt that going with something slightly more realistic like how the land before time would have made the danger and the perils in the adventure even stronger. Every time I see those T. rex onscreen I have a hard time taking them seriously. But other than that looks interesting so far. 

It doesn't seem to have any sort of complex story going on. Most of the focus is on the young Dino getting back to his herd befriending the little boy. Admittedly this isn't the first time these sort of stories have been done but I'm curious to know what else is it going to offer. The relationship between the Dino and his boy have to be strong enough to hold the entire film if that's what it's ultimately going to be about.

Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment:
Bare in mind that even though this is all hypothetical to where this is a story if the asteroid/comet never hit earth, that single act could have changed and altered many things. Humans probably would have never existed as well as bananas, ect. ¬†It was because of that supposed meteor/comet (or whatever took out the dinosaurs) that brought mass extinction upon the dinosaurs, as well as other plants and organisms, so that the small mammals would have less predators to worry about, thus could thrive and evolve into humans and other recognizable animals.

Another interesting fact is that modern humanoids and dinosaurs could not coexist for one reason; there was much more oxygen on the earth during the dinosaurs' reign.¬†Humans wouldn't be able to breathe the thick O2 if they lived with dinos back before the Cretaceous-Paleogene extinction event and vice versa -- if Dinos lived with us today they wouldn't have enough oxygen to breathe for that's how they evolved to be so large. Humans evolved with the post extinction oxygen levels and most modern plants. Humans weren't always the omnivorous brutes we see today.

Why Pixar chose the whitest looking humanoid to play the homosapien-esque character is beyond me. Depends on what era it is and where they are geographically. Is this before or after the ice age? Is the story set in the Cretaceous/Paleogene era where the continents are still extremely close to each other? Or is it simply based in Africa?¬†Humans just recently migrated out of Africa hundred thousand years ago, which is why there are different skin tones based on sun exposure. So it'd take a while for this little boys' and his people to have such lighter skin than their ancestors for this take place. At least several or more million years after those dinosaurs comically watched the meteor/comet pass by, humans were evolving, born, migrated to cooler climates and then we get the main story we see for any of this to make sense.

But I know... This is just a what if made for fun animated film for kids and a story about friendship. Looks good, I'm gonna see it. Just wanted to point this out if no one already did.

Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment:
Wow... No words for how amazing this will be... (Okay, I actually do have some):

It's unbelievable how much animation has changed within twenty years. The details in this trailer are absolutely stunning, and at some points it actually felt like I was watching a movie shot in real life. Then there are those cartoonish looking characters that appeal to audiences of all ages, which is a good thing. Finally, the trailer itself was able to tell a story really without any dialogue. Most trailers we see today need a lot of dialogue to tell what the plot is gonna be for the movie, but this trailer didn't need it. It's a challenge to tell what a movie will be about within a two minute trailer that has minimal dialogue, but of course, Pixar can achieve doing that and even anything.

This looks like a cute movie & I HATE 2 be this guy, but it is driving me crazy!- there is literally no way humans & dinosaurs would exist together. The "age of the mammals" was owed to the extinction of the dinosaurs, which opened the pathway, not just 4 our evolution, but the evolution of multiple other organisms 2, such as- wait 4 it- grass & trees! W/ the dinos gone, there were hundreds of niches that needed 2 b occupied: there r no large grazing herbivores? Natural selection gave us bison. Pack carnivores? Wolves. Small arboreal foragers? & yes, I do know that there were mammals were around w/ dinosaurs, but the biggest 1 discovered was basically a large flying squirrel. Not that impressive is it?

Comment: Why are you people saying Inside Out was good? There was nothing special about it. I almost fell asleep during the movie because the plot was so weak. Of course, Pixar is basically the only giant in animation in the US because Dreamworks just makes 2 hours of jokes and call it a movie. They make a whole movie out of minions because they want to follow trends of what works instead of just making good movies. Toys coming to life, rats cooking in parisian kitchens, a space romance, those are what sound magical. Inside Out kept moving back and forth from inside Riley's mind to the real world and the plot was all over the place. I love Pete Docter, but let's be honest, it's okay to say Pixar messed up when they don't make a good movie.

The dinosaurs up-close look a bit too cartoony for my tastes, but from a distance, they look pretty good. The story does seem pretty heartwarming,¬†I'm getting sort of a "Land Before¬†Time" vibe from it. And the animation on the landscapes, water, trees and mountains are absolutely gorgeous. And of course, we have another movie in the Pixar franchise that isn't a sequel.

I gotta say, Pixar: I hope you don't disappoint. :)
